<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="unit_circle">
  <title>Unit Circle</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we will introduce the trigonometric functions using the Unit Circle.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection>
    <title>Unit Circle</title>
    <definition xml:id="def_unit-circle">
      <title>Unit Circe</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>unit circle</term>
          <idx>
            <h>unit circle</h>
          </idx>
          is a circle whose radius is 1 and whose center is at the origin of a rectangular plane (or <m>xy</m>-plane). The equation for the unit circle is
          <me>
            x^2+y^2=1
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      Let <m>t</m> be a real number. Recall from <xref ref="def_radian">Definition</xref> that a radian measure of a central angle, <m>t</m>, is defined as the ratio of the arc length <m>s</m> to the radius <m>r</m>. In other words, <m>t=\frac{s}{r}</m>. In the unit circle, the radius is <m>r=1</m>, and the angle in radians is equal to the arc length, <m>t=s</m>. We will let <m>t</m> be in radians. The circumference of the unit circle is
      <m>2\pi r=2\pi \cdot 1=2\pi</m>.
    </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-unit-circle-with-arc-length" width="60%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.25]
        \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
        \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
        \draw (0,0) circle (1);r
        \draw (0,0) -- (57.3:1);
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.25)]0,0) arc (0:57.3:0.25) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1] {\(t\)};
        \node[right] at (30:1.1) {\(s=t\)};
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1) arc (0:57.3:1);\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      If <m>t\geq0</m>, we can imagine wrapping a line around the unit circle, marking off a distance of <m>t</m> in a counterclockwise direction,
      and labeling that point <m>P(x,y)</m>, whic becomes the terminal point. If <m>t\lt 0</m> then we would wrap in a clockwise direction.
    </p>
    <image xml:id="fig-unit-circle-with-arc-length-wrapped" width="55%">
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.25]
        \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
        \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
        \draw (0,0) circle (1);
        \draw[-stealth] (1,0) -- (1,1.25);
        \draw[blue] (0.95,0.25) -- (1.05,0.25);
        \draw[blue] (0.95,0.5) -- (1.05,0.5);
        \draw[blue] (0.95,0.75) -- (1.05,0.75);
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (1,0) -- (1,1);
        \draw[blue] (14.3:0.95) -- (14.3:1.05);
        \draw[blue] (28.6:0.95) -- (28.6:1.05);
        \draw[blue] (43:0.95) -- (43:1.05);
        \draw[blue] (57.3:0.95) -- (57.3:1.05);
        \draw[blue, dashed] (57.3:1) -- (1,1);
        \draw[line width=2pt,blue] (0:1) arc (0:57.3:1);
        \filldraw[black] (1,0) circle(1pt);
        \filldraw[black] (57.3:1) circle(1pt) node[above,yshift=5] {\(P(x,y)\)};
        \filldraw[black] (1,1) circle(1pt) node[right, xshift=2] {\(t\)};
        \draw (0,0) -- (57.3:1);
        \draw ([shift=(0:0.25)]0,0) arc (0:57.3:0.25) node[midway,right,xshift=0.1] {\(t\)};\end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <p>
      If <m>t\gt2\pi</m> or <m>t\lt -2\pi</m>,
      then the length is longer than the circumference of the unit circle and you will need to travel around the unit circle more than once before arrive at the point
      <m>P(x,y)</m>.
      Therefore, we can conclude that regardless of the value of <m>t</m>,
      we have a unique point <m>P(x,y)</m> that lies on the unit circle.
      We call <m>P(x,y)</m> the <em>point on the unit circle that corresponds to <m>t</m></em>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsec_trig-functions">
    <title>Trigonometric Functions</title>
    <p>
      <idx>
        <h>trigonometric functions</h>
      </idx>
      The <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-coordinates for <m>P(x,y)</m>
      can then be used to define the six trigonometric functions of a real number
      <m>t</m>:
    </p>
    <tabular><row>
      <cell><em>sine</em></cell>
      <cell><em>cosine</em></cell>
      <cell><em>tangent</em></cell>
      <cell><em>cosecant</em></cell>
      <cell><em>secant</em></cell>
      <cell><em>cotangent</em></cell>
    </row></tabular>
    <p>
      which are abbreviated as
      <em>sin</em>, <em>cos</em>, <em>tan</em>,
      <em>csc</em>, <em>sec</em>, and <em>cot</em>, respectively.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-of-trig-functions"><title>Definition of Trigonometric Functions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>trigonometric functions</h>
            <h>of real numbers</h>
          </idx>
          Let <m>t</m> be any real number and let <m>P(x,y)</m> be the terminal point on the unit circle associated with <m>t</m>. Then
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin t\amp =y \amp  \cos t\amp =x \amp  \tan t\amp =\frac{y}{x},~(x\neq0)</mrow>
            <mrow>\csc t\amp =\frac{1}{y},~(y\neq0) \amp  \sec t\amp =\frac{1}{x},~(x\neq0) \amp  \cot t\amp =\frac{x}{y},~(y\neq0)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-def-trig-function-unit-circle" width="75%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3.5]
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.15,0)--(1.15,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.15)--(0,1.15) node[above]{\(y\)};
            \draw (0,0) circle (1);
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (45:1) node[midway,above,yshift=5] {1};
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.707106781187,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-2] {\(\cos t\)};
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0.707106781187,0) -- (0.707106781187,0.707106781187) node[midway,right,yshift=-6] {\(\sin t\)};
            \draw (0.607106781187,0) -- (0.607106781187,0.1) -- (0.707106781187,0.1);
            \filldraw[black] (45:1) circle(1pt) node[above right] {\(P(x,y)\)};
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.25)]0,0) arc (0:45:0.25) node[midway,right,xshift=1] {\(t\)};
            \node at (22.5:1.1) {t};\end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          Notice that <m>\tan t</m> and <m>\sec t</m> re undefined when <m>x=0</m> and <m>\csc t</m> and <m>\cot t</m> are undefined when <m>y=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>t</m> be the angle that corresponds to the point <m>P(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})</m>. Find the exact values of the six trigonometric functions corresponding to <m>t</m>: <m>\sin t</m>, <m>\cos t</m>, <m>\tan t</m>, <m>\csc t</m>, <m>\sec t</m>, <m>\cot t</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The point <m>P(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2},-\frac{1}{2})</m> gives us <m>x=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m> and <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}</m>. Then we have
          <md>
            <mrow> \sin \theta\amp =y=-\frac{1}{2},\amp \csc \theta\amp =\frac{1}{y}=\frac{1}{-\frac{1}{2}}=-2,</mrow>
            <mrow> \cos \theta\amp =x=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, \amp \sec \theta\amp =\frac{1}{x}=\frac{1}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{3}}=\frac{2\sqrt{3}}{3},</mrow>
            <mrow> \tan \theta\amp =\frac{y}{x}=\frac{-\frac{1}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}=-\frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}=-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3},\amp \cot \theta\amp =\frac{x}{y}=\frac{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}}{-\frac{1}{2}}=-\sqrt{3}.</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Trigonometric Functions of an Angle</title>
    <definition xml:id="def_6-trig-functions-unit-circle">
      <title>Trigonometric Functions of an Angle</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <idx>
            <h>trigonometric functions</h>
            <h>of angles</h>
          </idx>
          If <m>\theta</m> is an angle with radian measure <m>t</m>, then the
          <term>six trigonometric functions</term> become
          <md>
            <mrow>\sin \theta\amp =y \amp  \cos \theta\amp =x \amp  \tan \theta\amp =\frac{y}{x},~(x\neq0)</mrow>
            <mrow>\csc \theta\amp =\frac{1}{y},~(y\neq0) \amp  \sec \theta\amp =\frac{1}{x},~(x\neq0) \amp  \cot \theta\amp =\frac{x}{y},~(y\neq0)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the exact values of the six trigonometric functions for
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=0</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            When <m>\theta=0</m> radians (<m>0^{\circ}</m>), the point on the circle is <m>P(1,0)</m>.
          </p>
          <image xml:id="exmp-6trig-0" width="55%">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.25]
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
              \draw (0,0) circle (1);
              \draw[blue,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (1,0) node[black,above right,yshift=0.1] {P(1,0)};
              \filldraw[blue,line width=2pt] (0:1) circle(1pt);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Then <m>x=1</m> and <m>y=0</m> gives us
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin 0\amp =\sin 0^{\circ}=0, \amp \csc 0\amp =\csc  0^{\circ}=\mbox{undefined},</mrow>
              <mrow>\cos 0\amp =\cos 0^{\circ}=1, \amp \sec 0\amp =\sec  0^{\circ}=1,</mrow>
              <mrow>\tan 0\amp =\tan 0^{\circ}=0, \amp \cot 0 \amp =\cot  0^{\circ}=\mbox{undefined}.</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            When <m>\theta=\frac{3\pi}{2}</m>
            radians (<m>270^{\circ}</m>),
            the point on the circle is
            <m>P(0,-1)</m>.
          </p>
          <image xml:id="exmp-6trig-3pi2" width="55%">
            <latex-image> \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.25]
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
              \draw (0,0) circle (1);
              \draw[blue,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0,-1) node[black,below right,xshift=0.1] {P(0,-1)};
              \filldraw[blue,line width=2pt] (270:1) circle(1pt); \draw[-stealth] (0:0.3) arc (0:270:0.3);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Then <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=-1</m> gives us
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\sin 270^{\circ}=-1, \amp \csc \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\csc  270^{\circ}=-1,</mrow>
              <mrow>\cos \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\cos 270^{\circ}=0, \amp  \sec \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\sec  270^{\circ}=\mbox{undefined},</mrow>
              <mrow>\tan \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\tan 270^{\circ}=\mbox{undefined}, \amp \cot \frac{3\pi}{2}\amp =\cot  270^{\circ}=0</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <m>\theta=5\pi</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Since <m>\theta=5\pi>2\pi</m>, our angle is greater than one full rotation of a circle. We first subtract <m>\theta</m> by one rotation, <m>2\pi</m>, to get
            <me>
              5\pi-2\pi-=3\pi
            </me>
            Once again, since we have completed more than one full rotation, we can repeat the previous step:
            <me>
              3\pi-2\pi=\pi
            </me>
            The values of the six trigonometric functions when
            <m>\theta=5\pi</m> are equal to those when <m>\theta=\pi</m>.
            Notice that <m>5\pi</m> and <m>\pi</m> are
            <em>coterminal angles</em>, both ending at the point<m>P(-1,0)</m>.
          </p>
          <image xml:id="exmp-6trig-5pi" width="55%">
            <latex-image> \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.25]
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.25,0)--(1.25,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
              \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.25)--(0,1.25) node[above]{\(y\)};
              \draw (0,0) circle (1);
              \draw[blue,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (-1,0) node[black,above left,xshift=-0.1] {P(-1,0)};
              \filldraw[blue,line width=2pt] (180:1) circle(1pt); \draw [-stealth,domain=0:5*pi,variable=\t,smooth,samples=75] plot ({\t r}: {0.1+0.03*\t});
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <p>
            Since <m>x=-1</m> and <m>y=0</m> we have
            <md>
              <mrow>\sin 5\pi\amp =0, \amp  \cos 5\pi\amp =-1, \amp  \tan 5\pi\amp =0,</mrow>
              <mrow>\csc 5\pi\amp =\mbox{undefined}, \amp  \sec 5\pi\amp =-1, \amp  \cot 5\pi\amp =\mbox{undefined}. </mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </task>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Finding the Exact Values of the Trigonometric Functions for <m>\theta=45^{\circ}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact values of the six trigonometric functions for
          <m>\theta=45^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We begin by drawing a right triangle with a base angle of
          <m>45^{\circ}</m>
          in the unit circle.
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-1st-quad-triangle-45" width="55%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=4.5]
            \draw[-stealth] (0,0)--(1.1,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
            \draw[-stealth] (0,0)--(0,1.1) node[above]{\(y\)};
            \draw (0:1) arc (0:90:1);
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (45:1) node[midway,above,yshift=5] {1};
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.707106781187,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-3] {\(x\)};
            \draw[line width=2pt] (0.707106781187,0) -- (0.707106781187,0.707106781187) node[midway,right,xshift=3] {\(y\)};
            \filldraw[black] (45:1) circle(0.5pt) node[right,xshift=2.3] {\(P(x,y)\)};
            \draw ([shift=(0:0.2)]0,0) arc (0:45:0.2) node[midway,right,xshift=1] {\(45^{\circ}\)};
            \draw (0.627106781187,0) -- (0.627106781187,0.08) -- (0.707106781187,0.08);
            \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0.9,0.9) node[above] {\(y=x\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          Since the first quadrant has <m>90^{\circ}</m>,
          at <m>\theta=45^{\circ}</m>, the point
          <m>P</m> lies on the line that bisects the first quadrant.
          This means the point <m>P</m> is on the line <m>y=x</m>.
          Since <m>P(x,y)</m> also lies on the unit circle, whose equation is
          <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, we get
          <md>
            <mrow>x^2+y^2\amp = 1</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+x^2\amp = 1 \amp(\mbox{since } y=x)</mrow>
            <mrow>2x^2\amp = 1</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2\amp = \frac{1}{2}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \amp(\mbox{since } y=x)</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Then
          <md>
            <mrow> \sin 45^{\circ} \amp=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp \csc  45^{\circ}=\frac{1}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}\amp=\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow> \cos 45^{\circ} \amp=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}=\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \amp \sec  45^{\circ}=\frac{1}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}\amp=\sqrt{2}</mrow>
            <mrow> \tan 45^{\circ} \amp=\frac{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}=1 \amp \cot  45^{\circ}=\frac{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}{\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}}\amp=1</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="ex_unit-circle-30">
      <title>Finding the Exact Values of the Trigonometric Functions for <m>\theta=30^{\circ}</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the exact values of the six trigonometric functions for
          <m>\theta=30^{\circ}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, we will draw a triangle in a circle with an angle of
          <m>30^{\circ}</m>
          and a second triangle with an angle of
          <m>-30^{\circ}</m>
          .
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-1st-quad-triangle-30" width="75%">
          <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3.25]
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (-1.15,0)--(1.15,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
          \draw[stealth-stealth] (0,-1.15)--(0,1.15) node[above]{\(y\)};
          \draw (0,0) circle (1);
          \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (30:1) node[midway,above,yshift=0.2] {1};
          \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (-30:1) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {1};
          \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.866025403784,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {\(x\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt] (0.866025403784,0) -- (0.866025403784,0.5) node[midway,left,xshift=-0.2] {\(y\)};
          \draw[line width=2pt] (0.866025403784,0) -- (0.866025403784,-0.5) node[midway,left,xshift=-0.2] {\(y\)};
          \filldraw[black] (30:1) circle(1pt) node[right,xshift=0.1] {\(P(x,y)\)};
          \draw ([shift=(0:0.25)]0,0) arc (0:30:0.25) node[midway,right,xshift=0.,yshift=0.1] {\(30^{\circ}\)};
          \draw (0.766025403784,0) -- (0.766025403784,0.1) -- (0.866025403784,0.1);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
        </image>
        <p>
          This gives us two 30-60-90 triangles.
          Notice this now gives us one larger triangle whose angles are all <m>60^{\circ}</m>.
          Thus we have an equilateral triangle, with each side of length 1.
        </p>
        <sidebyside>
          <image xml:id="fig-30-60-90-derive-two">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=6]
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (30:1) node[midway,above,yshift=0.2] {1};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (-30:1) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {1};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (0.866025403784,0) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {\(x\)};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0.866025403784,0) -- (0.866025403784,0.5) node[midway,left,yshift=-0.2] {\(y\)};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0.866025403784,0) -- (0.866025403784,-0.5) node[midway,left,yshift=0.2] {\(y\)};
              \filldraw[black] (30:1) circle(0.5pt) node[left,xshift=-10] {\(P(x,y)\)};
              \draw ([shift=(0:0.15)]0,0) arc (0:30:0.15) node[midway,right,xshift=0.04,yshift=0.1] {\(30^{\circ}\)};
              \draw ([shift=(0:0.15)]0,0) arc (0:-30:0.15) node[midway,right,xshift=0.0,yshift=-0.1] {\(30^{\circ}\)};
              \draw ([shift=(210:0.15)]30:1) arc (210:270:0.15) node[midway,below,xshift=-0.1] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
              \draw ([shift=(90:0.15)]-30:1) arc (90:150:0.15) node[midway,above,xshift=-0.1] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
              \draw (0.786025403784,0) -- (0.786025403784,0.08) -- (0.866025403784,0.08);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
          <image xml:id="fig-30-60-90-derive-one">
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=6]
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (30:1) node[midway,above,yshift=0.2] {1};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (-30:1) node[midway,below,yshift=-0.1] {1};
              \draw[line width=2pt] (0.866025403784,-0.5) -- (0.866025403784,0.5) node[midway,left,yshift=-0.2] {\(1=2y\)};
              \filldraw[black] (30:1) circle(0.5pt) node[left,xshift=-10] {\(P(x,y)\)};
              \draw ([shift=(-30:0.15)]0,0) arc (-30:30:0.15) node[midway,right,xshift=0.04] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
              \draw ([shift=(210:0.15)]30:1) arc (210:270:0.15) node[midway,below,xshift=-0.1] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
              \draw ([shift=(90:0.15)]-30:1) arc (90:150:0.15) node[midway,above,xshift=-0.1] {\(60^{\circ}\)};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
          We see that <m>1=2y</m> so <m>y=\frac{1}{2}</m>. Then by the Pythagorean Theorem,
          <md>
            <mrow>x^2+y^2\amp = 1^2</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)^2\amp = 1</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2+\frac{1}{4}\amp = 1</mrow>
            <mrow>x^2\amp = \frac{3}{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          Giving us the following triangle
        </p>
        <image xml:id="fig-30-60-90-sides" width="55%">
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=4.5]
            \draw[-stealth] (0,0)--(1.1,0) node[right]{\(x\)};
